<subSubSection id="88DE6550FFACFFC30FFCBAA5C168F914" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="C07B36DBFFACFFC30FFCBAA5C168F914" blockId="14.[160,1157,1460,1727]" pageId="14" pageNumber="288">
<taxonomicName id="07C44D58FFACFFC30FFCBAA5C360FA66" authorityName="Illiger" authorityYear="1807" box="[192,293,1460,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Lampyridae" genus="Amydetes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F2B0EAC9FFACFFC30FFCBAA5C360FA66" box="[192,293,1460,1485]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="288">Amydetes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by the presence of an antenna with more than 20 antennomeres, a remarkable feature among insects (
<bibRefCitation id="A4554B2AFFACFFC30D1ABAC6C0EDFA44" author="Minelli A" box="[550,680,1495,1519]" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" pagination="6680" refId="ref16670" refString="Minelli A. 2017. The insect antenna: segmentation, patterning and positional homology. J Entomol Acarol Res. 49 (1): 6680." type="journal article" year="2017">Minelli 2017</bibRefCitation>
), and a row of dense bristles in the metacoxa (
<bibRefCitation id="A4554B2AFFACFFC30F99BAEBC3ABF9B9" author="Silveira LFL &amp; Mermudes JRM" box="[165,494,1530,1554]" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" pagination="201 - 248" refId="ref17270" refString="Silveira LFL, Mermudes JRM. 2014 a. Systematic review of the firefly genus Amydetes Illiger, 1807 (Coleoptera: Lampyridae), with description of 13 new species. Zootaxa. 3765 (3): 201 - 248." type="journal article" year="2014">Silveira and Mermudes 2014a</bibRefCitation>
). The complex antenna, which is allometric and very often asymmetric (
<bibRefCitation id="A4554B2AFFACFFC30E1BB90CC398F99E" author="Nunes VCS &amp; Souto PM &amp; Minelli A &amp; Stanger-Hall K &amp; Silveira LFL" box="[295,477,1565,1589]" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" pagination="1 - 10" refId="ref16732" refString="Nunes VCS, Souto PM, Minelli A, Stanger-Hall K, Silveira LFL. 2020. Antennomere numbers in fireflies (Coleoptera: Lampyridae): unique patterns and tentative explanations. Zool Anz. 286: 1 - 10." type="journal article" year="2020">Nunes et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), likely helps males in finding sessile, probably flightless females, but the latter remain unknown. The genus was recently reviewed by 
<bibRefCitation id="A4554B2AFFACFFC30CB0B92EC2B5F9D1" author="Silveira LFL &amp; Mermudes JRM" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" pagination="201 - 248" refId="ref17270" refString="Silveira LFL, Mermudes JRM. 2014 a. Systematic review of the firefly genus Amydetes Illiger, 1807 (Coleoptera: Lampyridae), with description of 13 new species. Zootaxa. 3765 (3): 201 - 248." type="journal article" year="2014">Silveira and Mermudes (2014a)</bibRefCitation>
showing a diversity of circadian habits across species 
<emphasis id="F2B0EAC9FFACFFC30C66B973C122F9D1" box="[858,871,1634,1658]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="288">–</emphasis>
some are diurnal, others nocturnal. All species, diurnal or nocturnal, glow with a green, bluish-green light (
<bibRefCitation id="A4554B2AFFACFFC30B07B994C290F914" author="Viviani VR" pageId="14" pageNumber="288" pagination="129 - 145" refId="ref18078" refString="Viviani VR. 2001. Fireflies (Coleoptera: Lampyridae) from Southeastern Brazil: habitats, life history, and bioluminescence. Ann Entomol Soc Am. 94 (1): 129 - 145." type="journal article" year="2001">Viviani 2001</bibRefCitation>
; LS pers. obs.). Females and immature stages unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
